04767nam a22007215i 9780857455222DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574552227 a10.1515/97808574552222doi  a(DE-B1597)637216  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHM554b.A68 2009 7aSOC0190002bisacsh04a303.6/603aAn Anthropology of War :bViews from the Frontline /ced. by Alisse Waterston. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (204 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrelude: An Accountability, Written in the Year 2109 -- tIntroduction: On War and Accountability -- tChapter 1 Ten Points on War -- tChapter 2 Global Warring Today “Maybe Somebody Needs to Explain” -- tChapter 3 Global Fractures -- tChapter 4 Seeing Green Visual Technology, Virtual Reality, and the Experience of War -- tChapter 5 Military Occupation as Carceral Society Prisons, Checkpoints, and Walls in the Israeli-Palestinian Struggle -- tChapter 6 War and Peace in Colombia -- tChapter 7 The Continuum of Violence in Post-war Guatemala -- tChapter 8 Mother Courage and the Future of War -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs we move deeper into the twenty-first century, power, lethal force, and injustice continue to explode violently into war, and the prospects for lasting peace look even bleaker. The horrors of modern warfare - the death, dehumanization, and destruction of social and material infrastructures - have done little to bring an end to armed conflict. In this volume, leading chroniclers of war provide thoughtful and powerful essays that reflect on their ethnographic work at the frontlines. The contributors recount not only what they have seen and heard in war zones but also what is being read, studied, analyzed and remembered in such diverse locations as Colombia and Guatemala, Israel and Palestine, Iraq, Afghanistan, and Haiti. In detailed reports from the field, they reflect on the important issue of “accountability” and offer explanations to discern causes, patterns, and practices of war. Through this unique lens, the contributors provide the insight and analysis needed for a deeper understanding of one of the greatest issues of our times. Contributors: Avram Bornstein, Paul E. Farmer, R. Brian Ferguson, Lesley Gill, Beatriz Manz, Carolyn Nordstrom, Stephen Reyna, Jose N. Vasquez  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aWar and society. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh1 aBornstein, Avram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarmer, Paul E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerguson, R. Brian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGill, Lesley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManz, Beatriz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordstrom, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReyna, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVasquez, Jose N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaterston, Alisse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaterston, Alisse, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745522240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857455222423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857455222/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alle